          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">Norwegian spy</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopolitics.world/email/images/gp-nov-28-2.jpg" alt="Norwegian spy" href="https://www.geopolitics.world" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">The recent arrest of a 27-year-old Norwegian man on <a href="https://apnews.com/article/us-russia-espionage-arrest-embassy-norway-arctic-9aabf55ae20cffc9082df002a9976e0a" target="_blank">espionage charges</a> for allegedly aiding Russia and Iran has sparked widespread concern and highlighted Norway‚Äôs strategic vulnerabilities. The suspect, employed as a security guard at the US Embassy in Oslo and linked to a dormant security company, is accused of collecting sensitive information that could threaten US interests.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">His academic background in national security at the University of Tromso and visits to Kirkenes, near the Russian border, have intensified scrutiny, especially given the university‚Äôs connection to previous espionage cases like that of Russian spy <a href="https://www.thebarentsobserver.com/security/russia-prisoner-swap-includes-tromso-university-illegal-mikushin/165177" target="_blank">Mikhail Mikushin</a>. The arrest transpires against a backdrop of escalating espionage activity in Norway, including cases of Russian spies posing as diplomats and covert operations near NATO facilities. These developments emphasize the growing challenge of safeguarding national security in a region increasingly targeted by foreign intelligence services.‚Äã</p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-divider border-width="1px" border-style="solid" border-color="lightgrey" padding="10px 12px" />
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>
