          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">Mosque survey dispute</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Clashes in Sambhal, Uttar Pradesh, reveal the <a href="https://www.dw.com/en/india-mosque-survey-dispute-erupts-into-deadly-clashes/a-70879085" target="_blank">rising tensions</a> over religious and historical disputes in India. This conflict stems from a court survey investigating claims that the Shahi Jama Masjid was built on the site of a Hindu temple, which angered many Muslims. This issue is similar to the <a href="https://www.dw.com/en/india-modi-inaugurates-controversial-ayodhya-temple/a-68048499" target="_blank">Ayodhya dispute</a>, where a Hindu temple was built on the ruins of a mosque.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Protesters who opposed the survey violently clashed with police, leading to four deaths. In response, authorities imposed curfews, banned gatherings, and shut down internet services to restore order. This incident highlights the increasing religious division in India. Critics say that the ruling party‚Äôs actions support claims that question the historical existence of mosques, worsening communal divides. The situation shows the delicate balance of secularism in India‚Äôs democracy and raises concerns about the growing marginalization of minority communities amid a rise in religious and political majoritarianism.</p>
        </mj-text>
    </mj-section>

